	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Columbus, Ohio - June 2004<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 6, 2006</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Note from me: Hey all, I’d been meaning to do this for sometime now. I wanted to move all my Tournament Reports from the Decipher and DGMA sites to Decktech and Gameplayersnetwork since they are easier to find here and I’m worried that Decipher’s two sites will go down eventually. I wouldn’t want to lose all these awesome memories. So here they are, archived, for your amusement. Feel free to give reviews with your thoughts and memories of the events or to simply let me know how you liked the read. <br />
<br />
Mr. Sullivan goes to Origins<br />
<br />
Last year, 2003 Origins was the highlight of my LOTR career so far. I placed 3rd overall in the Premier Series Event netting me a sweet 400$. In fact, the entire top four was made up of fellow Canadians. Mathieu Brochu, Josh Cornwell-Mott and Dominic Gaudreault placed first, second and fourth, respectively. It was a glorious event. I&#39;m hoping that this year will be just as full of good memories and success as was the case last year. <br />
<br />
Pre-Tourney Jank<br />
My weapon of choice this year is for sure going to be a dwarf fellowship. I have never had so many site nine victories as of late as I have thanks to Gimli and Durin III. I have tried various styles of focus for my dwarves. First I tried a possession-heavy version that packed hand axes, Baruk Khazads and stacked many skirmish pumps on Loyalty Unshaken (obviously this started Sindri). However, my most recent build starts Linnar and is less inclined towards winning skirmishes as it is surviving and making double moves with ease. My teammate, Dominic, finally talked me into playing with a second Ring of Fury and a second Ring of Guile to go get one of my two Blood Runs Chill or Honed or whatever. I was mighty stubborn about putting them in but he talked me into it. The shadows that give me fellowship the most heart-ache seem to be Morgul Orcs and Sauron Orcs. Since both of this cultures share the same minion-type, I&#39;ve decided to borrow a little Euro-tech and threw in 2 Here Lies Balin, SoF, to increase my chances of winning against this tough shadows. <br />
Which brings me to my shadow choice. I have three different shadows that I still can&#39;t decide between. Two of which are Morgul Orc (one is a swarm version and the other is more beatdown). The beatdown version can win against almost all fellowships but actually has some difficulty with Dwarves since both the Twilight Witch King and Ents of Fanghorn Toldea don&#39;t win their skirmishes as much. Since I&#39;m expecting to see a ton of Dwarves, maybe this isn&#39;t the best idea. The swarm version packs 4 Whelps and 4 Goblin Runners but I haven&#39;t much experience playing with this vcrsion and I think there are a great deal of fellowships that might give it trouble. Plus, I&#39;m expecting people to pack a lot of Orc-hate so I&#39;m nervous to be playing them. The third shadow choice are Corsairs. They certainly have the tools necessary to slow a dwarf deck to a halt and can do very well against almost all fellowships except for a Gondor-Gandalf mix which seems to really tear me a new one. I think that I&#39;ll opt for the Morgul Orc swarm version since that would make the most sense on day one. I&#39;m only playing with 7 Nazgul though in a 34-card shadow. My reasoning is that I&#39;ll be able to pull one with my site 4 fetch enduring Nazgul site and I&#39;m playing 4 Morgul Skulkers so I should be able to always have a Nazzie when I need one. Jonas Skali and Dominic both disagree with me but I&#39;m a stubborn moron and I&#39;ll take my chances. <br />
Joining me on this trip and forming Team KwyjiboKardz are my usual teammates, Dominic Gaudreault and Matthew Yakobina. Our fourth and guest member for Origins is none other than Syracuse&#39;s own, Kirk England. The team is split in half with two members playing LOTR and the other two playing Marvel. It should be a very different experience than usual. <br />
For my DGMA Fantasy team, I picked myself, Josh &#39;Tech Tactic&#39; Cornwell-Mott, Steve &#39;I&#39;m not playing in the PSE&#39; Jones, Thomas Mitchell and my own padawan learner, Geoff Smith. I think I stand a decent chance in winning this thing for once. <br />
<br />
Thursday, June 24th, 2004<br />
&#39;The Grapes of Wrath&#39;<br />
So I&#39;m up at 5 in the morning or so and jump in the shower to spare my driving mates the joy of traveling 14 hours in a car with an unwashed Irishman (just ask the Malboeuf brothers what this is like). I get to Dom&#39;s around 6am and Yako is up and ready but Dominic is sound asleep as usual. We drag him in the car and start the long drive. <br />
We hit the U.S. Border around 8h30 in the morning and I&#39;m bracing myself for what is always lots of fun in trying to explain to the border guard where we&#39;re going and why. For once, he actually skims by the details on what the tournament is about and instead decides to ask me when was the last time I was fingerprinted. I think about it for a second and answer, &#39;um? at birth?&#39; To which Dominic, in the back seat, erupts in laughter (always helpful at customs when your friends are laughing). So then Dom and I get into an argument in French as to if you&#39;re fingerprinted at birth or not and Dom seems to think that fingerprints always means a police officer is involved. Anyway, we miraculously get waived thru and get to Syracuse a couple hours later. <br />
At this point, my throat is really starting to hurt and I know I&#39;m coming down with something so luckily Kirk England has this Tylenol Sore Throat medicine that I nail back like a shot of whiskey. Makes me feel better right away. <br />
The rest of the drive is fairly uneventful save for the gigantic monsoon which hits us 2 hours out of Columbus. I haven&#39;t seen rain like that in a long time. I&#39;m about to tell my traveling companions that we should think about building an ark when finally the rain subsides. I&#39;m about an hour away from Columbus (7pm) when Dom starts complaining that he has to pee real bad. I&#39;m like, &#39;Hey man, we&#39;re an hour away. Can you just hold it in?&#39; And he says, &#39;fine but if we&#39;re not there by 8:10pm, then I&#39;m peeing in your car.&#39; So this gives me some extra motivation. <br />
Anyway we pull into Columbus around 8pm and I get off the exit and start driving wildly down North Broadway Street trying to get to the hotel in ten minutes before Dom&#39;s bladder decides to empty on my plush bucket seats. I manage to hit every light on the way there and at 8:09pm I&#39;m at the intersection where the Super 8 motel we are staying at is situated. Unfortunately I hit the red light and two minutes later (longest light ever), Dom announces, &#39;OK, here we go?&#39; and I hear Kirk&#39;s Gatorade bottle suddenly filling up with some sort of liquid in the back seat. GROSS.<br />
So I park the car real fast and run inside to the front desk to check in. While the clerk is pulling out my room keys, Dom moseys on in and places a half-full Gatorade bottle on the front desk with a big smile on his face. All he can say is, &#39;it&#39;s hot.&#39;<br />
Anyway the free shuttle service to get to Origins is really erratic and doesn&#39;t work well if you plan on going out to the pub afterwards so we drive downtown and park in an outdoor parking lot. Kirk and Dom pick up their badges while Yako and I bump into Brochu and his crew. We decide instead of checking out the PSQ and stuff, we should just go eat and drink so we hit up the Red Star Tavern and Dom is introduced to his first baby-back rib experience. Dom thinks they&#39;re amazing but Kirk and I know better and enjoy our beverages far more than the food. An hour or two later, we&#39;re back at the hotel and crashing to save up energy for the PSE Day One the next day?<br />
<br />
Friday, June 25th, 2004<br />
Day One<br />
&#39;I better not go 3-5 again&#39;<br />
So as usual, I get up crazy early at 6 or so cuz I&#39;m so nervous about playing 8 rounds and pulling another Vegas-type of performance. So after giving myself two deck checks, Kirk is nice enough to lend me the extra Lemenya I need to make my shadow viable. I won a foil set of SOG at Vegas with Jake Denley so I dip into there and borrow some nice foils to round out my deck. I also lend a few to Kirk for his corsairs. Kirk, Yako and myself hit up the Bob Evans for a decent breakfast before driving out without Dom (he&#39;s gonna try the shuttle) to the convention centre. This time, we park in a multi-level parking garage since it&#39;s only 7 bucks for the entire day. Good deal. <br />
When the DGMA crew arrives (head judge Matt Clemens and his cronies), I see they all have Tim Horton&#39;s coffee. I am insanely jealous and immediately inquire as to where I can obtain such wonderful Canadian java?! It&#39;s a few miles away so I ask nicely if they can bring me some the next day. <br />
So this is my favourite part where I get to see all the great guys I haven&#39;t seen since either Vegas or GenCon last year. Geoff Smith, John Curran, Mike French and a ton of other cool guys have all made it out this year to Origins. Mike Girard also makes an appearance and will be doing DGMA event coverage (he rocks the house at that). I see he&#39;s brought a cell phone that takes pictures so he tests it out on me and here&#39;s the handsome result. (I look like a cross between Michael Moore and some random jewish movie director).<br />
So Pittsburg&#39;s own, Steve Miller, joins at the last second to make it an even 100 players for Day One Premier Series Origins. Here we go?<br />
Round One<br />
? Opponent: Kisser of strange women, Mike Noonan <br />
? Deck: Elf-Gondor - Morcs (Morgul Orcs)<br />
? Good: Mike is an awesome opponent and I just wish I could have been paired up later<br />
? Bad: I advanced very slowly with my fellowship since I wanted to discard his Asfaloth at my underground site 4. He was playing Galadriel as the Ring-Bearer and I assumed he was going to transfer Asfaloth from Arwen to Galadriel at site 2 or 3. <br />
? Ugly: Mike doesn&#39;t transfer Asfaloth to his ring-bearer against my obvious swarm deck so I pull out 7 or 8 minions at site 4 to kill Galadriel and make it a fast game. Mike&#39;s next card was Aragorn, Ranger of the North (*whew*)<br />
? Result: FW shadow kill site 4<br />
? 1-0<br />
Well getting that first win under your belt certainly goes a long way toward making top 16. Your confidence is immediately put in the right place and your SOS won&#39;t be as terrible. I&#39;m happy that my padawan learner, Geoff Smith, also won his first match. He&#39;s given me a really cool site marker, a foil What is Thy Bidding, My Master from SW:CCG. He&#39;s using a foil The Circle is Now Complete and I think they&#39;re bring us the luck we need. <br />
Round Two<br />
? Opponent: Hawaiian shirt-wearing, Joe Lewis <br />
? Deck: Shire Countryside / Lost to the Goblins corruption<br />
? Good: Joe was a fantastic opponent and I look forward to playing him again<br />
? Bad: I was GREATLY inexperienced playing against both his fellowship AND his shadow<br />
? Ugly: Unfortunately Joe is playing the Binding Ring which is pretty much an auto-loss against my shadow. I overwhelmed Gimli pretty early which was his tech to set up a good underdeeps and draw engine.<br />
? Result: FW shadow kill site 5<br />
? 2-0<br />
Geoff also wins his second game so all is well.<br />
Round Three<br />
? Opponent: Anvil-dropping hero, Matt Ward<br />
? Deck: Dworcs (Dwarves with Morgul Orcs)<br />
? Good: Matt wins the award for being my favourite opponent throughout the weekend.<br />
? Bad: This mirror match provided a tough match-up for both of us<br />
? Ugly: I ran into site nine with 5 companions and no more tricks up my sleeve (I had used up all my Ring of Guiles, Here lies Balin and Honeds). If he had a decent shadow draw, it was all over for me for sure. Luckily, he didn&#39;t.<br />
? Result: FW fellowship win site nine<br />
? 3-0<br />
Well, well, well? Geoff and I are both 3-0 at this point. My favourite part for me, though, is the fact that I have 2 shadow kills and a fellowship win. I&#39;m really happy to see that my deck can easily win both sides and that I&#39;m not reliant on one single strategy. Geoff&#39;s Lost to the Goblin deck can only win with the shadow so he&#39;s playing a much riskier strategy there.<br />
Round Four<br />
? Opponent: California&#39;s own &#39;I draw into my only Durin III at site one every time&#39;, Michael Perruca<br />
? Deck: Beasterlings/Dwarf-Elf Shoulder to Shoulder<br />
? Good: This was a perfect match for my shadow cuz silly little Michael is using the Binding Ring<br />
? Bad: I win the die roll since we both bid zero and elect to go first. Now remember that my shadow should auto-win this match. So what do I do? I not only elect to go first, but I double move, FOR NO REASON, from site 2 to 4.<br />
? Ugly: 2 big easterlings with bows and polearms come down at site 5 and wipe out my entire fellowship.<br />
? Result: FL shadow kill site 5<br />
? 3-1<br />
Crap, what a stupid mistake. Especially in that I had a perfect shadow hand to drop on him at four but I was forced to discard it at site 5 due to the site text of the Flat. I played so bad. However, I never make more than one serious mistake in a day so hopefully this is it.<br />
For the first time ever, I think, the DGMA gives a quick lunch break during a PSE. So I grab a 6.50$ Cheeseburger with terrible fries and expensive orange juice. I sit outside in the grass with Geoff Smith (who also lost), his brother Madison and a few other cool cats. Geoff and I give ourselves a pep talk in that we only have to win 3 of the next 4 matches. It&#39;s not that hard, right? Well, I&#39;m pretty calm and collected to I give it my best?<br />
Round Five<br />
? Opponent: Donald Roeber<br />
? Deck: Beasterling / Dwarf<br />
? Good: Donald was a great calm opponent which I really needed since I was nervous as hell against his shadow<br />
? Bad: Both our decks were bad match-ups for dwarves so it was tough on both of us.<br />
? Ugly: I got lucky and pulled my Enquea at site 8 when he had 5 burdens. <br />
? Result: FW shadow kill site 8<br />
? 4-1<br />
Round Six<br />
? Opponent: Nathanial Eiskat<br />
? Deck: Threat Naz / Merry&#39;s Swordthain HIDAN <br />
? Good: My old fellowship this guy is playing! Oh and Brian Fred rocks by the way.<br />
? Bad: I make a potentially game-losing mistake at site 6 by playing minions when I obviously need him to move into site 7 with 6 companions so I can draw like a madman. <br />
? Ugly: He counters by making THE game-losing mistake by ballooning back up to 6 or 7 companions before single moving into 7.<br />
? Result: FW, site 7 shadow kill<br />
? 5-1<br />
Now at this point, I&#39;m probably into day two but I&#39;m not sure. I really need to win one more of my next two games to assure myself a spot in day two.<br />
Round Seven<br />
? Opponent: My man, the irish dude himself, Matt Norton<br />
? Deck: Elven Telepathy with Gandalf MoW, Threat Naz<br />
? Good: Matt is one of the calmest players I&#39;ve ever met<br />
? Bad: His shadow was SO INEFFECTIVE against my dwarves, it wasn&#39;t even funny<br />
? Ugly: I pulled out 2 massive swarms which was one too many in the end<br />
? Result: FW shadow kill site 7<br />
? 6-1<br />
OMG, I&#39;m in day two! <br />
Round Eight<br />
? Opponent: Ex-World Champion, Mathieu Brochu<br />
? Deck: Dwarves with Moria<br />
? Good: I don&#39;t think I&#39;ve ever played a game against Brochu where I didn&#39;t swarm him at site 4<br />
? Bad: He bids three and his site 4 is Anduin Banks which helps me swarm better<br />
? Ugly: Gollum, Dark as Darkness, is really effective<br />
? Result: FW shadow kill site 4<br />
? 7-1 !!<br />
I finish in a very impressive 2nd seed right behind Josh Cornwell-Mott. Canadians grab the first two spots which I&#39;m really happy about. In fact, of the top 16, SIX are Canadians. <br />
So after telling a ton of people that we are hitting up O&#39;Shaunessey&#39;s Irish Pub, me and a bunch of guys head on over to the Arena District where the pub is located. <br />
We start off as a group of about 12-14 guys and are soon joined by the entire Decipher DGMA judging staff which was a great surprise. John Patchell also makes an appearance which is great and the entire Quebec contingent shows up. We get a really cute waitress, Michelle, who has the best personality I&#39;ve ever seen in a waitress so it makes the evening much more fun for Mike Noonan and myself. Colorado&#39;s Chris Williams orders up some tequila shots for him and I but it smells SO BAD that I can&#39;t go near it. Chris polishes them both off (I should mention that the word &#39;shot&#39; is a gross underestimation of how big these glasses of tequila were). So Chris is eleven sheets to the wind in about 5 minutes and everyone is having a great time. Although my fish sandwich was yucky. <br />
So I&#39;ve had way too much to drink so Kirk England drives us home but it takes us 20 minutes to get out of the parking lot since there is only one exit open at night. So all the cars in the parking lot get this huge bottleneck-effect happening on the first two levels. What a nightmare. <br />
I fall asleep realizing that I&#39;m probably going to be paired up against Hanh (Brochu&#39;s girlfriend and first female LOTR player to ever make top 16 at a PSE, I believe). So I&#39;m worried since Brochu will surely aid Hanh is teching against my dwarves really well. <br />
<br />
Saturday, June 26th, 2004<br />
Day Two PSE<br />
&#39;I&#39;ll be lucky to make it past my first pairing&#39;<br />
So this time, I get up even earlier, but Kirk is game for hitting up the Bob Evans breakfast place with me so we go and I have the traditional Day Two Eggs Benedict with Canadian Bacon no less. I&#39;m also sporting my Canadian Olympic bucket hat that I hope will bring me some luck and drive patriots like Mike French completely insane when they realize they are losing to a Canuck. <br />
I had the intention of skipping into the tournament room with Josh in a real fairy-like entrance but he was no where to be found so I just waltzed in and was greeted by some very generous DGMA judges who had brought me some Tim Horton&#39;s coffee. My secret tech is now complete.<br />
So Hanh and I set up and get ready to play our first game of a best of three-series match-up. We have 3 and a half hours to play three games. At first, I didn&#39;t think this would be an issue?<br />
Game One<br />
? Opponent: The lovely Dung-Hanh (two-time Arwen championship winner)<br />
? Deck: Easterlings / Dwarves<br />
? Good: Hanh played a great game<br />
? Bad: Greatest Kingdom of my people was in her opening hand and it really hurt my deck more than I expected.<br />
? Ugly: At site nine, I get a huge amount of orcs on Gimli (I have 27 strength I believe). Anyway, not only do I not overwhelm Gimli, but 4 Honeds later, I actually lose the skirmish to a 29-strength Gimli and all my Morcs die.<br />
? Result: Loss site 9<br />
? 0-1<br />
Well I think about this game a lot outside and realize that I can&#39;t let her set up her fellowship. Otherwise, she&#39;ll just repeatedly hang on to her Honeds. So I&#39;m going to have to start hitting her at site 4 or earlier regardless of the damage her Greatest Kingdom is doing to my 68-card deck. <br />
Game Two<br />
? Good:  Hanh is really a great opponent. She&#39;s much better than she was last year where I beat her twice in two days at Origins. <br />
? Bad: Once again, she pulls that damn Greatest Kingdom at site one without even having to use the site text to get it.<br />
? Ugly: This time I really concentrate on the early hit and I pull out a huge squad at site 4 to overwhelm Gimli. She only needed one Honed to survive I believe.<br />
? Result: Win shadow kill site 4<br />
? 1-1<br />
Wow, I actually managed to pull out a forced 3rd game. However, the first game took 90 minutes so at this point, we only have a hour left in the most important match of them all. So we get to it pretty fast. Here is a picture of us playing in the third match. On my left, I have my little buddy, Drew L. On my right, I have my not-so-little buddy, Bryce S. To Bryce&#39;s right is Spokane&#39;s Dan Curran (brother to the King of Scrubs himself). To his right, is Head Judge and fetcher-of-Tim-Horton&#39;s-Coffee, Matt Clemens. On the other side of the table, on Hanh&#39;s left, is Guillaume who&#39;s a really great kid from Quebec City and one of Brochu&#39;s crew. Standard directly behind Guillaume, there appears to be a man who has shoved a entire frozen turkey under his shirt. <br />
Game Three (tie-breaker)<br />
? Good: I&#39;ve been giving Hanh a small kiss on the cheek good-luck each game so three games means three free kisses J<br />
? Bad:  I should mention at some point that Brochu built Hanh the worst shadow build I have ever seen. <br />
? Ugly: I&#39;ll have to say once again that the shadow she was playing was abysmal.<br />
? Result: Win site 9 fellowship<br />
? 2-1<br />
I was so nervous playing Hanh in first round since I felt bad about playing someone I knew really well and secondly, because I knew Brochu had made the deck. But since I defeated her, my confidence was soaring so I was really anxious to play the next round against? Mike French! OH NO! The Vegas PSE champ himself I have to take care of now. I don&#39;t expect it to be easy at all. But I&#39;m still full confident that I can defeat him. <br />
The matches against Hanh took 3 hours and 15 minutes or so, I really don&#39;t want that to happen again so Mike and I get started right away.<br />
Game One<br />
? Opponent: Mike French<br />
? Deck: Man-Elf / Corsair<br />
? Good: This was a really fun match. When Mike is winning, he is always really calm and makes jokes like crazy.<br />
? Bad: I made some pretty serious mistakes this game in terms of being too confident in my shadow. But after all those shadow kills over the last two days, can you blame me?<br />
? Ugly: Nothing, it was a great game<br />
? Result: Loss site 9 <br />
So once again, I lose the first match and am forced to win-out which I find really challenging but in a good way. The next match and the one after were quite easily the most stressful games I&#39;ve played in a long time. They took everything out of me to try and win. I had to concentrate SO much on these games since the match-up was clearly favoured to Mike&#39;s fellowship. In fact, the matches wrecked my mind so much that I wasn&#39;t able to take notes after the games so I have no idea what happened. I&#39;m pretty sure they were BOTH shadow kills but I can&#39;t be sure. Here&#39;s a picture of one of the matches when things weren&#39;t going so well for Mike. That&#39;s Mike trying to work his way out of a hard swarm. That&#39;s me on the right acting like an idiot, as usual. That&#39;s Chris Tubman in the middle who appears to be looking the wrong way (actually, he&#39;s more into the Dalton-Brochu match). Mike and I were the featured match-up of the quarter-finals which was really flattering since Brochu and Dalton were playing each other. I would think that match would be more interesting. For a full description of what went on in those two last games (as well as the first), check out this site where Mike Girard did a fantastic play-by-play.<br />
<br />
Anyway, I end up making some really key decisions at site 9 on how to activate the most threats possible and thus, killing his entire fellowship before the fierce skirmish. It worked out really well and it was very hard to see how I was going to win it. Even Mike thought for a moment that he had the game won. But I pulled off a 2-1 victory over a disappointed Mr. French and I&#39;m sure he&#39;ll get me next time.<br />
Next, I&#39;m forced to move onto Brad Eire. So I really don&#39;t think that I should have been able to beat Mike French&#39;s deck. His fellowship had so many tools to handle my shadow. I think I just got a little lucky maybe and played really smart in those last two games, I suppose.<br />
 <br />
So I&#39;ve made it to the semi-finals against the great Brad Eire (who&#39;s last name I continuously misspell). I don&#39;t mind losing at all to Brad at this point since I think both he and I equally deserve our moment in the sun since neither of us have ever won a PSE. So it&#39;s a best-of-three as usual and I know for certain that time won&#39;t be a factor for Brad cuz I know he plays quickly and thinks even quicker. Oh by the way, did I mention that I had a sore throat all week and this morning I woke up unable to produce sound from my mouth? I must have contracted laryngitis or something cuz I was unable to speak all day long choosing to play Secrets of the Shire with Hahn and Mike French. However by Brad&#39;s game most of my voice had come back so I was able to chat a little more (probably the leading factor of my demise).<br />
 <br />
Game One<br />
? Brad&#39;s Deck: Corsair / Man-elf (must be my worst match-up, I wonder if I can beat it again).<br />
? Good: Playing against Brad is so relaxing, it&#39;s fantastic.<br />
? Bad: I got really really bad draws all game long. Bloods Runs Chill was playing cache-cache.<br />
? Ugly: I didn&#39;t draw into any of my seven Nazgul until the very end of the game so my morcs weren&#39;t terribly effective. Nice cakewalk for Brad.<br />
? Result: Loss site 9<br />
0-1<br />
 <br />
So I go outside to think about what I have to do to win. If I don&#39;t get my Blood Runs Chill early, I can&#39;t safely run against his shadow since it can actually kill me if he swarms and/or I lose initiative thanks to the War Galley. As for his fellowship, it seems to be less teched against my deck than Mike French&#39;s version. So if I could beat Brad, I could beat Mike right?<br />
 <br />
To give you an idea of how the second game went, here&#39;s a picture of me trying to figure out how to pull a win out of my bum-bum. Ouf? I don&#39;t look very happy in that picture at all. That&#39;s my man, Brian Fred, on my right. And behind him on the left is 2nd place finisher at the Continentals, Maximillian Bouchard from Quebec. <br />
 <br />
Anyway, I&#39;ve managed to win out against both Hanh and Mike after losing the first match so I guess I&#39;ll just have to do it again against Brad. Here we go..<br />
 <br />
? Game Two<br />
? Good: I bid 3 to go first against his Corsairs. This is my first time changing my bidding strategy all weekend and I think it was a really smart move.<br />
? Bad: The draws were even WORSE this game. Everytime Brad would double move, I would reconcile into 5 free people&#39;s cards. YUCK<br />
? Ugly: I experienced, for the first time, the Castamir with Halberd at site two. Bye bye, Smeagol and Thrarin and I don&#39;t have my Blood Runs Chill to double move L<br />
? Result: Loss at site 9<br />
? 0-2<br />
 <br />
So Brad moves on to the finals against Mathieu Brochu who brings home the gold for Canada and Quebec. In fact, 3 of the top four finishers (1st, 3rd and 4th) are all from Quebec. Last year all four were Canadian so I&#39;m almost disappointed. <br />
 <br />
Anyway I&#39;m really ecstatic about my 3rd place finish since I didn&#39;t expect to get past Hanh, let alone Mike French. The prize support is way better than I anticipated. I didn&#39;t think 3rd or 4th got any real money but I snagged 250$ as well as 275 Decipher Bucks which should net me 2 or 3 boxes of Shadows come winter!<br />
 <br />
So I hang around to watch the finals and then most everyone leaves shortly. I&#39;m lucky that I stuck around tho, cuz Decipher&#39;s own Kyle Heuer waltzes in with the best take-out Italian food I&#39;ve ever had. Bojo, Clemens and myself attack the garlic mashed potatoes, ravioli, pepperoni pizza, garlic cheese bread, meatballs, you name it, like there&#39;s no tomorrow. I was so hungry it was insane. So sitting back, I realize what a perfectly run PSE event it was. There was no stress that I could see compared to the usual complications (perhaps it has something to do with Josh getting eliminated first round? Nah, I think it has more to do with Matt Clemens running a great event). <br />
 <br />
So it looks like Clint Hays is organizing a pretty semi-serious Texas Hold &#39;Em tournament or something but I don&#39;t feel up to it so Will Cruse and I hit up O&#39;Shaunessey&#39;s expecting others to be there. They weren&#39;t but we have a great time eyeballing the really hot bus-girl. I think her name was Polly or something. I order up a couple pints of cider and Will asks the bartender for &#39;Vodka.&#39; To which the bartender naturally replies:<br />
&#39;With what?&#39;<br />
Will: &#39;nothing. Just vodka&#39;<br />
Bartender: &#39;Some ice?&#39;<br />
Will: &#39;No. Just straight up&#39;<br />
Bartender: &#39;So just vodka? Neat?&#39;<br />
Will: &#39;Neat? Whatever, just gimme some vodka&#39;<br />
Bartender: &#39;OK then. So which kind? Grey Goose? Iceberg?&#39;<br />
Patrick: &#39;I hear Stolies is good&#39;<br />
Will: &#39;ugh? Smirnoff&#39;<br />
 <br />
Bartender pours drinks and Will isn&#39;t more than two seconds into having a sip when he mentions, &#39;Wow.. this is pretty strong.&#39; So I fetch him some ice after 15 minutes or so and we&#39;re all good.<br />
 <br />
So no one shows up to the damn pub so we mosey on back to the convention center and some how walk right by the entire squad of Syracuse guys going to find us. In the convention center, I meet up with Yako, Dom and others and we head back to the pub where the &#39;Cuse guys are hard at work drinking. At this point, the exhaustion of playing 8 tough games sets in and I just wanna jet. I feel bad cuz I&#39;ve been meaning to get bombed with Mike Noonan for sometime now but I just don&#39;t have any gas left in my system.<br />
 <br />
Walking back to the parking lot, we see that it is completely filled with traffic since they, once again, closed the alternative exit off the 3rd floor. It looks like we&#39;ll have to drive down 4 floors worth of bumper-to-bumper and get out there. I guesstimate that it&#39;ll take 45 minutes or so. However, at the 3rd floor exit, I spot a tall drink of water trying to force open the unattended gate! And he succeeds! So I tell Dom and Yako to wait there and make sure to hold it open for me while Kirk and I get the car. <br />
 <br />
Kirk and I run up the stairs, drive down the ramp and take a right at the alternative (supposedly closed) exit. There we see Yako running towards my car, saying go!go!go! while Dom gets in casually. I&#39;m thinking for a sec, &#39;Well who&#39;s gonna hold open the gate?&#39; when I notice that the barrier gate has been completely snapped off. Dom is looking all guilty and I&#39;m happy that he won at least one arm wrestle over the weekend. <br />
 <br />
So we take off and I don&#39;t think I&#39;ll be parking in this lot again tomorrow. On the drive home, Yako and Dom are starving and I manage to find the elusive Tim Horton&#39;s that Matt Clemens had scoped out for me. So we get some club sandwiches, Tim Horton-style, and head back to the motel where I crash after two seconds.<br />
 <br />
Sunday, June 27th, 2004<br />
Day Two-Continentals<br />
&#39;Moon Kick!&#39;<br />
 <br />
Well I wake up CRAZY early this time around completely unable to sleep. So it&#39;s like 6h30 or so and I&#39;m all nervous again about scrubbing out of the continentals like I did last year so I get up and hit the Bob Evans restaurant by myself and scarf down two blueberry pancakes which should hold me over until supper hopefully. I get back and feel bad that I didn&#39;t wake up Kirk to come with me but now we really gotta go. So we swing by the Tim Horton&#39;s (now that I know where it is) and ask for a medium. They then hand me a large (or what they consider to be medium) and it strikes me how different and &#39;super-sized&#39; the American culture is. Because the coffee cups are made in Canada, it even says large on it, even tho I asked for a medium. Too weird..<br />
 <br />
So we arrive and I&#39;m really happy that the continentals are only 6 rounds. So I&#39;m playing the same deck since my mind is mush and I can hopefully just get thru it playing mostly by instinct. The problem is that my 8 games yesterday were untimed. Now I have to deal with the time aspect again and I&#39;m a little rusty.<br />
 <br />
Round One<br />
? Opponent: The PSE mid-event deck swapper himself, Dan Clark<br />
? Deck: Moria - Rohan<br />
? Good: Dan is a fun and talented opponent and I like playing against him<br />
? Bad: I played slow cuz moria is hard and Dan kept telling me to play faster. Poor patrick<br />
? Ugly:Well, it turns out that Plundered Armories is the secret tech against Dwarves. It completely obliterated me and I felt silly for playing Blood Runs Chill afterwards.<br />
? Result: FL shadow kill site 8<br />
? 0-1<br />
 <br />
Round Two<br />
? Opponent: Syracuse&#39;s own Seth Maser<br />
? Deck: Dwarves and corsairs<br />
? Good: This was a fun match<br />
? Bad: Seth is playing the binding ring which will send Gimli to the bottom of the sea in no time<br />
? Ugly: I had Gimli at 7 burdens by site 6<br />
? Result: FW corruption site 6<br />
? 1-1<br />
 <br />
Round Three<br />
? Opponent: The gentlemen from the East Coast, Doug Faust<br />
? Deck: Beasterlings / Elf-Man<br />
? Good: If Doug hadn&#39;t been playing the Binding ring, I think this would have been the worst possible match-up for my deck there is.<br />
? Bad: My site 5 (the Flat) is starting to really hurt my own fellowship often<br />
? Ugly: My dwarven axes discarded two of his most important companions. <br />
? Result: FW Shadow kill site 6<br />
? 2-1<br />
 <br />
Round Four<br />
? Opponent: From Hawaii to Colorado to Origins, Will Diniega<br />
? Deck: Bold men & Hate / Dwarf<br />
? Good: This was a good match-up for both of us and his shadow was really nice<br />
? Bad: My Durin III dies VERY early <br />
? Ugly: I didn&#39;t realize I would hit up dwarves so fast with burdens. I had him at nearly corrupted at site 6 and I ditched Enquea for some silly reason.<br />
? Result: FW Shadow kill site 7<br />
? 3-1<br />
 <br />
Round Five<br />
? Opponent: Michael Ium<br />
? Deck: Dwarf-Corsair<br />
? Good: This was really an excellent match-up for me in terms of skill required. I&#39;m always up for a challenge.<br />
? Bad: I got all four of my aggressions out early and he got zero<br />
? Ugly: I kept transferring my Ring of Fury for some silly reason. <br />
? Result: FW corruption site 6<br />
? 4-1<br />
 <br />
Cool! 4-1 record with one game left. If I win the next game I make top 8. I can&#39;t believe how well I&#39;ve been performing after a round one loss all weekend long. I am king of winning out.<br />
 <br />
? Round Six<br />
? Opponent: Mike Mendoza<br />
? Deck: Corsair, Elf-man with Isildur!<br />
? Good: Mike is a great opponent and real nice guy<br />
? Bad: This stupid game timed out and I really would have won the darn thing if I had more time. But It wasn&#39;t like I needed 5 more minutes. I really needed 15 minutes more so since I was so far from winning, I guess I can&#39;t be upset about it.<br />
? Ugly: stupid time. I went and played minions at site 8 knowing that he would double to 9 since there was 2 minutes left. I really should have let him double and try to wound him out with the threats. Like I did to Mike French. Oh well, it was a bad decision under a lot of pressure.<br />
? Result: Timed Loss site 8 (I of course give Mike the full win since not doing so is moronic). Lisa Gansky (Mike&#39;s GF) thanks me for giving Mike the full win to which I sarcastically reply, &#39;I was doing it more for my SOS than for Mike&#39;s record. Seriously tho, I can&#39;t believe some people don&#39;t concede timed losses. They really don&#39;t realize how much they&#39;re hurting their own record. Oh well? Poor Hanh was victim to this twice by some boys with very healthy appetites. <br />
? 4-2<br />
 <br />
So 4-2 is enough to get me 12th place which I&#39;m really disappointed with but out of 69 players, that really isn&#39;t too bad. So instead of leaving at 6pm to have supper, I stick around to watch the playoffs. <br />
 <br />
In the first round, I decide that watching Josh play Dan Clark will be the most fun since I say what Dan&#39;s deck can do to dwarves. It&#39;s actually a fairly stressful game to watch since Dan is trying to get Josh to play faster like he did with me. Dan should try playing a less complicated shadow since assignment takes forever if he wants to avoid timed wins (or losses). I learned my lesson against Mendoza and I don&#39;t think morcs make a very good day one deck since they take so long for your opponent to figure out what to do. I&#39;d rather play something straightforward like Beasterlings or something where it&#39;s just Bam! You&#39;re dead! <br />
 <br />
Anyway Josh actually pulls off a real miracle win at site nine against Dan&#39;s shadow and moves on to face Max from Quebec. Here I&#39;m torn as to who to root for since Max is from Quebec (as am I) but Josh is my good buddy. So I elect to root for the latter since I&#39;d really like to see Josh advance and actually win a title for once. So Max really hands it to Josh with an incredible number of corsair pumps in his deck. Neither Josh nor I saw them coming and Josh&#39;s companion count slowly reduced to nothing by the end. However, Dom was watching the game too and Dom is a big Street Fighter II player and ever since I started playing the Ring of Guile, I&#39;ve been meaning on adopting some sort of play style (a la Wingchow) that would be special for that card. I&#39;ve been working on my own but never did it, however, Josh figured one out that would honour Street Fighter II&#39;s best character, Guile, in only a way that Josh could. When using the Ring of Guile&#39;s text (twice in the game, by the way), Josh throws the card up and yells, &#39;Moon Kick!&#39; (which is already incorrect in that I think he does a Flash Kick in the game). And then when he gets out whichever skirmish event (Honed) he wants out of his discard pile, he spin-throws it at his opponent yelling, &#39;Sonic.. BOOM!&#39;. <br />
 <br />
Anyway I don&#39;t know if that makes any sense to any of you (You have to play more video games if not), but at the table where a large group of people were watching, only Dom and I were laughing hysterically. In the end, Josh loses, however, and Max moves on to face Alex K in the finals where Alex from Toronto brings home the bacon and gets Canada it&#39;s first ever North American Championship title. Look for my coverage of Alex&#39;s deck in an upcoming InQuest magazine. It was a perfect 2-site control Dunland build.<br />
 <br />
So after all this, Dom, Yako, myself, Will D, Chris W, Kirk E and Bryce S all head over to the Red Star Tavern where we sit outside on the terrace (patio, terrase or whatever it&#39;s called in your neck of the woods). Watching the sunset, having a pint (everyone got carded at this place so only Dom, Kirk and I enjoyed real drinks). And Chris Williams was smart enough to bring a deck of cards. So Yako pulls out a pad of paper as bookie and we play a few hours of Texas Hold Em. It was a ton of fun and a terrific way to close out the weekend. <br />
 <br />
The next day, we head back around 9 in the morning and try to get back to Montreal as fast as possible before Dom pees in my car again. <br />
 <br />
Props:<br />
? KwyjiboKardz.com for their great support and for sending rares so fast that I was able to play my Morc deck at Origins after deciding the very same week to try them on. <br />
? Dom and Yako for doing the trip and being part of the team even though they played Marvel exclusively <br />
? Kirk for being a great guest member of the team. <br />
? Geoff Smith for all the support and the great move token. How is it I didn&#39;t get any of that Jameson while I was there?! <br />
? Steve Miller for the great support and for making the trek from Pittsburg <br />
? My man Steve Jones for being the first person I see when I somehow managed to defeat Mike French and move into semi-finals. That hug was.. tech. <br />
? Brian Fred for letting me get aggressive with him when I was all stressed out cuz of Day Two PSE <br />
? Drew L for sitting beside most of my games and sending me good vibes <br />
? Mike Kessling for still being a smile-a-holic after all this time <br />
? Matt Clemens for running a terrific event and for getting me my FAVOURITE coffee in the world <br />
? Chris Williams, Will D and Bryce for making it down and having such a blast with us. That last night of poker was just too much fun. Chris going all-in with 7-2 off suit and winning was too weird <br />
? Hahn for the great match-up and for having a great attitude all weekend (and the kisses J <br />
? Brochu for winning it AGAIN. We had a blast <br />
? Mike French for somehow managing to lose to me (and to a Canadian at that!). See you at worlds, buddy <br />
? Brad Eire for being the one to knock me out. <br />
? John and Dan Curran for coming down from Spokane. Too much fun, guys. <br />
? Josh for making me laugh all weekend <br />
? All my great opponents from Day One of the PSE (Matt Ward, Joe Lewis and all the others). You guys made that day a lot of fun. Keep those great attitudes and bring them to worlds! <br />
? Peter Sundholm for being like an Energizer bunny. <br />
? Mike Girard for taking awesome pictures that totally immortalize these great moments. <br />
? Will Cruse for still being around and not giving up on LOTR <br />
? Kyle Heuer for the great food and fun times <br />
? Bojo for being Bojo (that&#39;s some cute kid you brought) <br />
 <br />
Slops:<br />
? To me for picking a motel WAY TOO FAR from the action. <br />
? To me again for forgetting a ton of people to give props to. (you guys know who you are and I don&#39;t mean to forget you J <br />
? To josh for running away after Dom, you and I bombarded the Pokemon playing area with HUGE paper airplanes. Dom and I turn around and poof! You&#39;re gone! And now we have to deal with the wrath of a bunch of upset tubby kids! <br />
 <br />
Thanks for reading this massive report. Make sure you ALL come to GenCon this August for the Worlds of LOTR. It&#39;s a terrific event and it is NOT to be missed.<br />
